name: kyma
description: A flexible and easy way to connect and extend enterprise applications in a cloud-native world
contribution_justification: Non-trivial contribution file in repository: <https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md>.
contribution_requirements_justification: https://github.com/kyma-project/community/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md contains general contribution guidelines and references to more docs with guidelines.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: Some documentation basics file contents found.
documentation_interface_justification: https://kyma-project.io/docs/ contains all docs including reference docs, like APIs or Kubernetes Custom Resources Definitions described in details
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/releases we keep all releases and always create the release branch, so all versions are available
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: SemVer is used in the project
version_tags_justification: We create a release branch and tag releases
release_notes_justification: https://kyma-project.io/blog/2019/7/12/release-notes-13/ we publish release notes in a form of a blog post, + additional release description on a GitHub release view
release_notes_vulns_justification:
We have a special template that all Product owners follow when providing input for release notes, and it addresses this topic https://github.com/kyma-project/community/blob/master/guidelines/templates/resources/release-notes-input.md#security-vulnerabilities-fixed. We also have a template to report security issues: https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/security-vulnerability.md

We use https://www.first.org/cvss/calculator/3.0 for assignments.
report_process_justification:
https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/issues/new/choose

2 templates are available, one for reporting bugs and one for requesting features.
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: User can report security issue by email https://github.com/kyma-project/community/blob/9d0c556335b2721f0892f2988af23d258e190304/README.md#security and also using special template https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/security-vulnerability.md
build_justification: For CI we use Prow and it is publicly available https://status.build.kyma-project.io/ and configuration is visible here https://github.com/kyma-project/test-infra
build_common_tools_justification: We use Prow which is common for Kubernetes/CNCF community
test_justification: All tests are automatically run on CI, not only unit tests but also an extensive suite of acceptance tests https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/tree/master/tests
test_most_justification: CI checks every pull request including those coming from forks and covers almost all use cases. We have a small list of manual tests that we regularly shrink
tests_are_added_justification:
Every functionality must have tests that are run by CI. Example from 1.3.0 release:
- Release notes about fetching specs with authorization https://kyma-project.io/blog/2019/7/12/release-notes-13/#application-connector
- PR with implementation and tests https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/pull/4661/files
warnings_fixed_justification: we use before commit hooks https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/components/service-binding-usage-controller/before-commit.sh and do golint. This is a continuous improvement to make sure it is checked everywhere the same way https://github.com/kyma-project/community/blob/master/sig-and-wg/sig-core/proposals/common-validator.md. We also use go vet https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/components/asset-store-controller-manager/Makefile#L57
warnings_strict_justification: Whenever we can we do it. So for example in the Console UI that us use to manage Kyma, if you want to remove an instance of a service, you get a proper warning of what it means and you need to confirm removal, same in case of other resources
know_secure_design_justification: We have a security team that we ask for support
know_common_errors_justification: selected members of the team had thread modeling training
crypto_published_justification: Kyma project runs on Kubernetes and uses all its features and doesn't apply custom cryptography.
static_analysis_often_justification:
Run on every master commit, e.g: 
https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/components/api-controller/Jenkinsfile#L65
dynamic_analysis_justification: It looks like it is not possible with Golang. We haven't found any tool we could use for that. If we are wrong and you know such a tool please let us know and we will integrate it -> http://slack.kyma-project.io. Govet is all we can do for now
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: It looks like it is not possible with Golang. We haven't found any tool we could use for that. If we are wrong and you know such a tool please let us know and we will integrate it -> http://slack.kyma-project.io. Govet is all we can do for now
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: It looks like it is not possible with Golang. We haven't found any tool we could use for that. If we are wrong and you know such a tool please let us know and we will integrate it -> http://slack.kyma-project.io. Govet is all we can do for now
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: It looks like it is not possible with Golang. We haven't found any tool we could use for that. If we are wrong and you know such a tool please let us know and we will integrate it -> http://slack.kyma-project.io. Govet is all we can do for now
discussion_justification:
GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.

Slack - https://kyma-community.slack.com/

documentation_achievements_justification:
https://github.com/kyma-project/kyma/blob/master/README.md
We have badges on top of the README

name: strongSwan
description: strongSwan is an open source IPsec-based VPN solution. It features IKEv1 and IKEv2 keying capabilities and runs on Linux 2.6, 3.x and 4.x kernels, Android, FreeBSD, Mac OS X and Windows.
sites_https_justification: All websites are using HTTPS, including the download page (https://download.strongswan.org).
description_good_justification: The index page has a list of supported features.
contribution_justification: https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/wiki/Contributions
license_location_justification: https://github.com/strongswan/strongswan/blob/master/LICENSE
floss_license_justification: strongSwan is licensed under the GPLv2 license, a commercial license is optionally available The GPL-2.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-2.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/wiki
documentation_interface_justification: For the C code Doxygen is used (https://www.strongswan.org/apidoc/), the config files and tool are documented extensively on the wiki and for the low-level VICI interface documentation is also available (https://github.com/strongswan/strongswan/blob/master/src/libcharon/plugins/vici/README.md).
repo_public_justification: The main repository is on git.strongswan.org with a mirror on GitHub, which both provide public URLs
repo_track_justification: The project uses Git to track the changes, who made them, and when they were made Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: Release candidates and developer releases are tagged in the repository
repo_distributed_justification: Git is used Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: Each release has a unique version number of the form x.y.z and releases are tagged in the Git repository
version_semver_justification: strongSwan uses the same format, but the version numbers are not strictly semantic (e.g. versions with changes of the middle number may include breaking changes)
version_tags_justification: Each release is tagged in the Git repository (signed)
release_notes_justification: An extensive changelog is provided in our issue tracker (https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/roadmap?completed=1), a blog post is also released for each version (https://www.strongswan.org/blog/)
release_notes_vulns_justification: This information is provided in the changelog plus a separate advisory on our blog for each CVE (https://www.strongswan.org/blog/tags/security+fix)
report_process_justification: Links to the issue tracker and mailing lists are provided on the support page (https://www.strongswan.org/support.html)
report_archive_justification: The issue tracker is searchable (https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/issues) and the for the mailing list an archive is provided (searchable with your favorite search engine)
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: A PGP key is provided on https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/wiki/FlawReporting
build_common_tools_justification: The build system is based on autotools
test_justification: Unit tests and integration tests are provided with the source code
test_invocation_justification: The unit tests can be via `make check` the integration tests need additional setup and separate script (described on https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/wiki/TestingEnvironment)
test_most_justification: Only the core library (libstrongswan) is currently thoroughly tested with unit tests, parts of other libraries (and plugins) are too, but the overall coverage is only slightly over 50%, the integration tests, however, cover more of the code base
test_policy_justification: That's definitely the case for library functions, for larger new features integration tests are usually added
tests_are_added_justification: New integration tests are often mentioned in the release notes (to serve as examples that showcase the new features)
tests_documented_added_justification: If appropriate we add tests if the submitter failed to do so
warnings_justification: The default CFLAGS include -Wall, however, some warnings are explicitly disabled
warnings_fixed_justification: On CI systems -Werror is used, so the build fails if there are any warnings
warnings_strict_justification: Currently used are  -Wno-format and -Wno-format-security (causing lots of warnings due to the use of custom printf-specifiers), and -Wno-pointer-sign (does not seem necessary anymore with current compilers)
crypto_call_justification: A primary purpose is to implement cryptography, however, it's possible to delegate most cryptographic operations to third-party libraries
crypto_working_justification: Default IKE and IPsec proposals don't include such algorithms, potential issues are described e.g. on https://wiki.strongswan.org/projects/strongswan/wiki/IKEv2CipherSuites
crypto_pfs_justification: IKE uses a separate DH exchange for every rekeying, for IPsec SAs PFS may additionally be enabled (to separate the keys from the IKE keys), however, the keys for the first IPsec SA negotiated with IKEv2 are always derived from the IKE keys
crypto_password_storage_justification: As client the plaintext password must be available (if not entered manually), and as server, most authentication protocols used via IKE rely on plaintext passwords as the password is never transmitted but only challenges and their responses, which require the password for verification
delivery_mitm_justification: The releases and tags in the Git repository are signed with PGP, all websites are exclusively available via HTTPS
static_analysis_often_justification: Currently only run for release candidates
dynamic_analysis_justification: strongSwan's own memory check tool is used on CI, parts of the code are fuzzed on OSS-Fuzz
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: OSS-Fuzz is used for parts of the code
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: There are no asserts (as in those provided by assert.h), but there are obviously a lot of runtime checks (e.g. for valid inputs in functions), and error handling for return values of called functions
crypto_weaknesses_justification: SHA-1 is required because the IKEv2 protocol relies it for some applications (e.g. NAT-D payloads), other than that stronger algorithms are preferred
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Continuous integration is implemented via Travis CI (https://travis-ci.org/strongswan/strongswan) and AppVeyor (https://ci.appveyor.com/project/tobiasbrunner/strongswan-52lo9)
discussion_justification: We provide an issue tracker and mailing lists (both linked on https://www.strongswan.org/support.html), GitHub may be used for pull requests
english_justification: All documentation is provided in English, the main language for the issue tracker and mailing lists is also English
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
implementation_languages: C, Shell, Java, Makefile, Objective-C, C++, M4, Python, Perl, Ruby, C#, Yacc, Lex, Ada, JavaScript

access_continuity_justification:
For DMaaP there are 5 committers and multiple contributors who are listed in:
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Resources+and+Repositories#ResourcesandRepositories-DataMovementasaPlatform
All 5 committers have access and rights to maintain the code base, approve and review incoming changes and release a new version of the artifact. This will let the project continue with minimal to no interruption if one person is incapacitated.
Also this project is controlled by the linux foundation so we can add more committers if needed
bus_factor_justification:
The current team working on the DMaaP Data-Router project inherited the code so the "bus factor" when calculated using the truck-factor tool estimated the "bus factor" to be 1. The team has since taken over and are not dependent on any one person and it can be seen in the commits here that there are 6 commit owners actively contributing and maintaining code. Commit owners listed alphabetically - (Fiachra Corcoran, Emmett Cox, Paul Dennehy, Ronan Keogh, Mariusz Sobucki, Conor Ward)
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/q/project:dmaap/datarouter+status:merged
documentation_architecture_justification:
Architecture of DMaaP Data-Router can be found in:
https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/dmaap/datarouter.git/docs/data-router/architecture.html
documentation_security_justification: A security sub-committee is driving all components release requirements, best practices. Agreed recommendations become integral parts of an ONAP release and are assessed during milestones. URL : https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/ONAP+Security+coordination The release note clearly states what has been achieved, along with the release checklists and links to individual JIRA items that covers the above security requirements.
documentation_quick_start_justification: Information on setting up ONAP can be found at https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guides/onap-developer/settingup/index.html
documentation_current_justification: Documentation is updated with each release.
documentation_achievements_justification:
The badge is visible on the project's page here:
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Data+Movement+as+a+Platform+Project
accessibility_best_practices_justificati:
The DMaaP Data-Router project does not have any user interface. It exposes an API and fulfills a contract
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=dmaap%2Fdatarouter.git;a=shortlog;h=HEAD
internationalization_justification:
The DMaaP Data-Router project does not have any user interface. It exposes an API and fulfills a contract
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=dmaap%2Fdatarouter.git;a=shortlog;h=HEAD
sites_password_security_justification: The project does not store passwords for authentication of external users
maintenance_or_update_justification: All major releases are tagged in gerrit and the artifacts are stored with the release information on onap.nexus. So we can access all old versions of the artifact. If and when a upgrade requires certain steps to be followed they are being added to the release documents as needed
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio:
Vulnerabilities can be reported using the link
https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=6591711
Currently we dont have any vulnerabilities reported, but the wiki page explains on how to report a vulnerability and how to report anonymously if you do not want the credit for it.
coding_standards_justification: Project uses Google Java Style with changes explained here - https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Java+code+style
build_standard_variables_justification: The application does not create native binaries as it creates a jar.
build_preserve_debug_justification: The application does not create native binaries as it creates a jar.
build_non_recursive_justification: The application does not create native binaries as it creates a jar.
build_repeatable_justification: All releases are tagged in gerrit(git), and the builds are controlled using jenkins. By providing the git tag information the same image can be build over and over again with same bit-for-bit result.
installation_standard_variables_justific: The compiled docker images and jar files can be installed/used as the user sees fit. Both run on JVM or docker. So there is no reason to selecting locations etc.
installation_development_quick_justifica:
The component requires only java and maven to begin with for a developer to quickly install and test it.
Even for deployment using OOM and the right amount of resources, we can deploy the full DMaaP/ONAP suite in less than a day. The steps are documented in
https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/oom.git/docs/oom_quickstart_guide.html
external_dependencies_justification:
External dependencies are controlled using the pom file, which can be found in the root folder of each of the projects modules
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=dmaap/datarouter.git;a=blob;f=datarouter-node/pom.xml;h=29e3ce4760e498ef3a5a9629981458cc738d08df;hb=HEAD
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=dmaap/datarouter.git;a=blob;f=datarouter-prov/pom.xml;h=0bb54170ee381f5fdeac7b7cf194865d4614a6c8;hb=HEAD
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=dmaap/datarouter.git;a=blob;f=datarouter-subscriber/pom.xml;h=87b82f1d0dbb6a04bec5b3bfbb95d1241d840e25;hb=HEAD
dependency_monitoring_justification:
NexusIQ sonar scan is run on the project on a weekly basis
https://jenkins.onap.org/view/dmaap/job/dmaap-datarouter-maven-clm-master/
updateable_reused_components_justificati: External components are maintained through Maven. The user can get a list of all included components using the maven dependency tree and can update or reuse as they see fit
interfaces_current_justification: We avoid depending on deprecated/obsolete functions.
automated_integration_testing_justificat:
Automatic test suites are run every time before merging the code. The code check in cannot pass without jenkins posting a +1 on the review.
https://jenkins.onap.org/view/dmaap/job/dmaap-datarouter-master-verify-java/
regression_tests_added50_justification: When regressions occur, we add tests for them.
test_statement_coverage80_justification:
We use sonar to measure the code coverage.
https://sonar.onap.org/component_measures?id=org.onap.dmaap.datarouter%3Aparent&metric=line_coverage
Coverage currently 81.8%
test_policy_mandated_justification:
Contributing guide lines for development is recorded in:
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies
implement_secure_design_justification: The project strives to be as simple as possible, to base access decisions on permission, to have every object checked for authority, using least privilege and minimizing common mechanisms.
input_validation_justification: The project implements CADI/AAF for Authorization and Authentication which implements the required checks.
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: Certificates are managed through AAF micro-service which will be deployed with ONAP suite
signed_releases_justification: All release artifacts are signed by the Linux Foundation prior to release.
version_tags_signed_justification: All releases (which are tagged major/minor/patch) are signed by Linux Foundation.
copyright_per_file_justification: All source and documentation files are required to have copyright notices
license_per_file_justification: All source and documentation files are required to have license statements
assurance_case_justification: AAF/CADI is itself a security framework for Authentication and Authorization. What it does is all documented in the initial docs. https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aaf/authz.git/docs/index.html
